“More than anything else New York is a city of superlatives, a place where the best, the brightest, the biggest is the norm.”
– Marilyn J. Appleberg

node.text: The courage of those among us who take care of the sick and dying are equal in courage to the dramatic feats of anyone we usually consider to have prowess or power. To persevere, without any expectation of assistance or recognition, is an act of heartbreaking heroism.

node.text: As Afghans flee the advancing Taliban and search for safety, neighboring countries fear an influx of refugees and the potential destabilization in the region caused by mass migration.  After accepting millions of Afghan refugees during the Soviet invasion and the civil war which followed, Pakistan is announcing that they will not accept more refugees.

node.text:
“I was driving down a road between Jodhpur and Jaisalmer in Rajasthan, India. It was sunny and sweltering hot at about 110°F (43°C), when the sky suddenly went dark and a pre-monsoon dust storm began. As the storm got stronger and more dramatic, the air became thick with dust. Through the haze, I could see these women huddled together off the side of the road protecting themselves from the driving wind. This region had been suffering from a drought for more than a decade and the women were singing a prayer for rain. I got out of the car, ran across a field and photographed them moments before the storm disappeared. Then the sun immediately came out, as if nothing had ever happened.”
